  "doc_id": "45897",
  "text": "Coronal flux ropes are also well-known to deviate from uniformly twisted configurations, but the detailed variation of q(r) is hard to quantify precisely from observations. [CITATION_1] reported on nonlinear force-free field (NLFFF) models for a sequence of flares in AR 11817, identifying a fieldline specific twist number T w ≡ L ∇ × B · B/(4πB 2 ) dl, which is readily integrated along each individual field line and relates well to the actual twist profile about its axis. [CITATION_2] identified how a complete flux rope structure was formed during eruption, typified by a varying-twist profile. Further out in the heliosphere, the magnetic topology of interplanetary (magnetic cloud) flux ropes can be studied in detail, and [CITATION_3] found many interplanetary CMEs that deviate from uniform twist, or linear force-free states.",
